In [[mathematics]], a '''deformation ring''' is a [[ring (mathematics)|ring]] that controls liftings of a representation of a [[Galois group]] from a [[finite field]] to a [[local field]]. In particular for any such lifting problem there is often a '''universal deformation ring''' that classifies all such liftings, and whose [[spectrum of a ring|spectrum]] is the '''universal deformation space'''.

A key step in [[Andrew Wiles|Wiles's]] proof of the [[modularity theorem]] was to study the relation between  universal deformation rings and [[Hecke algebra acting on modular forms|Hecke algebra]]. 

